  "prompt": "How does specific heat and heat capacity differ?",
  "response": "Specific heat and heat capacity are related concepts in thermodynamics, but they differ in their definitions and applications. Here's a breakdown of the differences:\n\n### 1. **Definition:**\n   - **Specific Heat (Specific Heat Capacity):**\n     - Specific heat is the amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of a unit mass (usually 1 gram or 1 kilogram) of a substance by one degree Celsius (or one Kelvin).\n     - It is an intensive property, meaning it is independent of the amount of substance.\n     - Units: \\( \\text{J/(g\u00b7\u00b0C)} \\) or \\( \\text{J/(kg\u00b7K)} \\).\n\n   - **Heat Capacity:**\n     - Heat capacity is the amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of an entire object or a specific quantity of a substance by one degree Celsius (or one Kelvin).\n     - It is an extensive property, meaning it depends on the amount of substance.\n     - Units: \\( \\text{J/\u00b0C} \\) or \\( \\text{J/K} \\).\n\n### 2. **Scope:**\n   - **Specific Heat:** Refers to the property of a material itself, regardless of its mass.\n   - **Heat Capacity:** Refers to a specific object or quantity of material and depends on both the material's specific heat and its mass.\n\n### 3. **Relation:**\n   - Heat capacity (\\( C \\)) can be calculated from specific heat (\\( c \\)) and mass (\\( m \\)) using the formula:\n     \\[\n     C = m \\cdot c\n     \\]\n   - For example, if you know the specific heat of water (approximately \\( 4.18 \\, \\text{J/(g\u00b7\u00b0C)} \\)) and the mass of a sample of water, you can calculate its heat capacity.\n\n### 4. **Example:**\n   - **Specific Heat:** The specific heat of water is \\( 4.18 \\, \\text{J/(g\u00b7\u00b0C)} \\). This means it takes 4.18 joules of energy to raise the temperature of 1 gram of water by 1\u00b0C.\n   - **Heat Capacity:** If you have 100 grams of water, the heat capacity would be \\( 100 \\, \\text{g} \\times 4.18 \\, \\text{J/(g\u00b7\u00b0C)} = 418 \\, \\text{J/\u00b0C} \\). This means it takes 418 joules of energy to raise the temperature of the entire 100-gram sample by 1\u00b0C.\n\n### Summary:\n- **Specific heat** is a property of the material itself (per unit mass).\n- **Heat capacity** depends on both the material and the amount of substance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
